                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p rend=\"align(right)\"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>\n                <date>October 19<hi rend=\"sup\">th</hi> Heshvan 15<hi rend=\"sup\">th</hi>.\n                5603</date>.</p>\n            <p>Dear Uncle.</p>\n            <p rend=\"indent(1)\">I should judge from your letter that when you wrote you had not<lb/>\n                received the <add>?</add> liner I had sent you by <persName>Mrs. Lyons</persName>,\n                who nevertheless<lb/> had promised to call on you on her journey to her new home.\n                But<lb/> I have little doubt that she fulfilled her promise by calling before\n                she<lb/> left, and that she likewise told <persName>aunt R</persName> all the\n                particulars about<lb/> the wedding. I am well aware that ladies like to hear\n                such<lb/> matters; but I am but little acquainted with them to give full<lb/>\n                particulars. The wedding however was a tolerably merry one,<lb/> and plenty to eat\n                and to drink was set before all the com-<lb/>pany. As usual some affronts were\n                given; since some persons<lb/> thought themselves entitled to an invitation which\n                was not extended<lb/> to them. Among the rest a cousin of the bride, who expected to\n                be <hi rend=\"underline\">unter</hi>-<lb/><hi rend=\"underline\">ferer</hi>, and not\n                being asked she and <sic>and</sic> husband did not come<lb/> at all. However this\n                you know is not uncommon; I myself staid till<lb/> near one o'clock; as they did not\n                sit down to supper till a quarter before<lb/> twelve, and I was expected to stay to\n                say prayers. It was rather<lb/> a later hour for me than I liked to remain out of\n                bed; but as there was<lb/> no help for it I had to submit.</p>\n            <p rend=\"indent(1)\">Old <persName>Mr Wolff</persName> has been at our house for some\n                weeks.<lb/> He had a cataract on one eye, and could not see well out of<lb/> the\n                other. He had accordingly an operation before<add>?</add> to remove<lb/> the\n                cataract from the one eye, already <date>Sunday</date> two weeks ago;<lb/> and as\n                yet he has not been down stairs. As my room is I think<lb/> the most convenient in\n                the house I gave it up to him; though I<lb/> do not hold him in very high\n                estimation, since he is for a European<lb/> as little of a Jew as ever I saw in my\n                life. However he too has<lb/> not escaped without his share of trouble. I hope that\n                in a week or two<lb/> he may be able to travel southwards as he lives in\n                    <placeName>Mobile, Alabama</placeName>; a person sick in a house makes a great\n                difference in all arrange<lb/>ments.</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3s46hs3r/canvas/p1"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
