          "annotations": [
            {
              "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3s46hs3r/canvas/p2/annopage",
              "type": "AnnotationPage",
              "items": [
                {
                  "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3s46hs3r/manifest/annotation/p2",
                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>As I am writing a message is brought that <persName>Rachel Pyke</persName>\n                    (<persName>Peixotto</persName>) was<lb/> last night confined; but the child is\n                dead. I do not admire that couple<lb/> much. I have recommended him to several\n                persons to give him goods<lb/> on commission; but he invariably has failed of paying\n                over what he<lb/> sold, and so he will get but little more from Jews. He has cost\n                me<lb/> besides somewhat like twenty Dollars in money, and more indirectly,<lb/> and\n                from me therefore he has nothing to expect. Upon the whole there<lb/> is little\n                satisfaction in doing anything for the poor of this community. They<lb/> generally\n                eat up what they get; and but small thanks do even fall to<lb/> my share at least; I\n                know not how it may be with other people. It<lb/> would not matter much if I were\n                rich; but having to work for every cent<lb/> I get, it is rather hard that so many\n                make constant claim to the<lb/> little I have, and do it in such a manner that a\n                refusal is out of my<lb/> power. I have determined at times not to be liberal; but I\n                see no way<lb/> whatever to avoid giving more than I should do for my means.\n                Still<lb/> as I am a single man and having no one whom I need work for, it\n                makes<lb/> but small odds at last, as I hope with God's Helping to be always able to\n                earn<lb/> my living; and if I have this respectably I have no right to ask for\n                more.</p>\n            <p rend=\"indent(1)\">My intention was to go to <placeName>New York</placeName> last\n                    <date>Sunday</date>. But <persName>Mr. S. Pesoa</persName><lb/> was on\n                    <date>Thursday</date> &amp; <date>Friday</date> so ill, that the Doctor had no\n                hopes of his<lb/> living to the utmost more than 72 hours. But last evening I\n                went<lb/> to see him, and he appeared to me not to be quite so sick as that he<lb/>\n                might not recover. <persName>Doctor Jackson</persName> happened to come in as I\n                was<lb/> going away, and I waited till he was going again, when he asked<lb/> to\n                ride down in his carriage, and took me to <placeName>8<hi rend=\"sup\">th</hi> &amp;\n                    Chestnut Streets</placeName><lb/> (believe in <placeName>8<hi rend=\"sup\">th</hi>\n                    below Walnut</placeName>); he then told me that there is but small<lb/>\n                probability of his recovery, yet there is no symptom which would make<lb/> his\n                disease necessarily fatal. So I trust, that the poor young man<lb/> may get up\n                again, especially as he has four to five children &amp; a helpless wife<lb/>\n                depending for support upon his daily exertions. I thought that the family might<lb/>\n                think it unkind in me to leave the city under these circumstances, so I\n                    reach<add>?</add></p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3s46hs3r/canvas/p2"
                }
